events.description: Roman emperor Theodosius I proclaims his eight-year-old son Honorius co-emperor.
events.html: • 393 – Roman emperor Theodosius I proclaims his eight-year-old son Honorius co-emperor.[1]

events.description: Using crossbows, Song dynasty troops soundly defeat a war elephant corps of the Southern Han at Shao.
events.html: • 971 – Using crossbows, Song dynasty troops soundly defeat a war elephant corps of the Southern Han at Shao.

events.description: The episcopal seat is moved from Nousiainen to Koroinen (located near the current centre of Turku) by the permission of Pope Gregory IX. The date is starting to be considered as the founding of Turku.
events.html: • 1229 – The episcopal seat is moved from Nousiainen to Koroinen (located near the current centre of Turku) by the permission of Pope Gregory IX. The date is starting to be considered as the founding of Turku.[2]

events.description: In the conflict between King Henry III of England and his rebellious barons led by Simon de Montfort, King Louis IX of France issues the Mise of Amiens, a one-sided decision in favour of Henry that later leads to the Second Barons' War.
events.html: • 1264 – In the conflict between King Henry III of England and his rebellious barons led by Simon de Montfort, King Louis IX of France issues the Mise of Amiens, a one-sided decision in favour of Henry that later leads to the Second Barons' War.[3]

entities.name: Simon de Montfort, 6th Earl of Leicester

events.description: Zhu Yuanzhang proclaims himself the Hongwu Emperor, beginning the Ming dynasty.
events.html: • 1368 – Zhu Yuanzhang proclaims himself the Hongwu Emperor, beginning the Ming dynasty.[4]

events.description: Having published nothing for eleven years, François Rabelais publishes the Tiers Livre, his sequel to Gargantua and Pantagruel.
events.html: • 1546 – Having published nothing for eleven years, François Rabelais publishes the Tiers Livre, his sequel to Gargantua and Pantagruel.

events.description: The deadliest earthquake in history, the Shaanxi earthquake, hits Shaanxi province, China. The death toll may have been as high as 830,000.
events.html: • 1556 – The deadliest earthquake in history, the Shaanxi earthquake, hits Shaanxi province, China. The death toll may have been as high as 830,000.[5]

events.description: James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray, regent for the infant King James VI of Scotland, is assassinated by firearm, the first recorded instance of such.
events.html: • 1570 – James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray, regent for the infant King James VI of Scotland, is assassinated by firearm, the first recorded instance of such.[6]

events.description: The Royal Exchange opens in London.
events.html: • 1571 – The Royal Exchange opens in London.[7]

events.description: The Union of Utrecht forms a Protestant republic in the Netherlands.
events.html: • 1579 – The Union of Utrecht forms a Protestant republic in the Netherlands.[8]

events.description: Blaise Pascal publishes the first of his Lettres provinciales.
events.html: • 1656 – Blaise Pascal publishes the first of his Lettres provinciales.[9]

events.description: The Principality of Liechtenstein is created within the Holy Roman Empire.
events.html: • 1719 – The Principality of Liechtenstein is created within the Holy Roman Empire.[10]

events.description: Georgetown College, the first Catholic university in the United States, is founded in Georgetown, Maryland (now a part of Washington, D.C.) when Bishop John Carroll, Rev. Robert Molyneux, and Rev. John Ashton purchase land for the proposed academy for the education of youth.
events.html: • 1789 – Georgetown College, the first Catholic university in the United States, is founded in Georgetown, Maryland (now a part of Washington, D.C.) when Bishop John Carroll, Rev. Robert Molyneux, and Rev. John Ashton purchase land for the proposed academy for the education of youth.[11]

events.description: Second Partition of Poland.
events.html: • 1793 – Second Partition of Poland.[12]

events.description: After an extraordinary charge across the frozen Zuiderzee, the French cavalry captured 14 Dutch ships and 850 guns, in a rare occurrence of a battle between ships and cavalry.
events.html: • 1795 – After an extraordinary charge across the frozen Zuiderzee, the French cavalry captured 14 Dutch ships and 850 guns, in a rare occurrence of a battle between ships and cavalry.

entities.name: Capture of the Dutch fleet at Den Helder

events.description: Slavery in Tunisia is abolished.
events.html: • 1846 – Slavery in Tunisia is abolished.[13]

events.description: Elizabeth Blackwell is awarded her M.D. by the Geneva Medical College of Geneva, New York, becoming the United States' first female doctor.
events.html: • 1849 – Elizabeth Blackwell is awarded her M.D. by the Geneva Medical College of Geneva, New York, becoming the United States' first female doctor.

events.description: In Montana, U.S. cavalrymen kill 173 Native Americans, mostly women and children, in what becomes known as the Marias Massacre.
events.html: • 1870 – In Montana, U.S. cavalrymen kill 173 Native Americans, mostly women and children, in what becomes known as the Marias Massacre.

entities.name: Native Americans in the United States

events.description: Anglo-Zulu War: The Battle of Rorke's Drift ends.
events.html: • 1879 – Anglo-Zulu War: The Battle of Rorke's Drift ends.

events.description: The Malolos Constitution is inaugurated, establishing the First Philippine Republic. Emilio Aguinaldo is sworn in as its first president.
events.html: • 1899 – The Malolos Constitution is inaugurated, establishing the First Philippine Republic. Emilio Aguinaldo is sworn in as its first president.

entities.name: List of presidents of the Philippines

events.description: Second Boer War: The Battle of Spion Kop between the forces of the South African Republic and the Orange Free State and British forces ends in a British defeat.
events.html: • 1900 – Second Boer War: The Battle of Spion Kop between the forces of the South African Republic and the Orange Free State and British forces ends in a British defeat.

events.description: Ålesund Fire: The Norwegian coastal town Ålesund is devastated by fire, leaving 10,000 people homeless and one person dead. Kaiser Wilhelm II funds the rebuilding of the town in Jugendstil style.
events.html: • 1904 – Ålesund Fire: The Norwegian coastal town Ålesund is devastated by fire, leaving 10,000 people homeless and one person dead. Kaiser Wilhelm II funds the rebuilding of the town in Jugendstil style.

events.description: RMS Republic, a passenger ship of the White Star Line, becomes the first ship to use the CQD distress signal after colliding with another ship, the SS Florida, off the Massachusetts coastline, an event that kills six people. The Republic sinks the next day.
events.html: • 1909 – RMS Republic, a passenger ship of the White Star Line, becomes the first ship to use the CQD distress signal after colliding with another ship, the SS Florida, off the Massachusetts coastline, an event that kills six people. The Republic sinks the next day.

events.description: The International Opium Convention is signed at The Hague.
events.html: • 1912 – The International Opium Convention is signed at The Hague.

events.description: The First Regional Congress of Peasants, Workers and Insurgents is held by the Makhnovshchina at Velykomykhailivka.
events.html: • 1919 – The First Regional Congress of Peasants, Workers and Insurgents is held by the Makhnovshchina at Velykomykhailivka.[14]

entities.name: Regional Congress of Peasants, Workers and Insurgents

events.description: The Netherlands refuses to surrender the exiled Kaiser Wilhelm II of Germany to the Allies.
events.html: • 1920 – The Netherlands refuses to surrender the exiled Kaiser Wilhelm II of Germany to the Allies.

events.description: The trial of the anti-Soviet Trotskyist center sees seventeen mid-level Communists accused of sympathizing with Leon Trotsky and plotting to overthrow Joseph Stalin's regime.
events.html: • 1937 – The trial of the anti-Soviet Trotskyist center sees seventeen mid-level Communists accused of sympathizing with Leon Trotsky and plotting to overthrow Joseph Stalin's regime.

events.description: Charles Lindbergh testifies before the U.S. Congress and recommends that the United States negotiate a neutrality pact with Adolf Hitler.
events.html: • 1941 – Charles Lindbergh testifies before the U.S. Congress and recommends that the United States negotiate a neutrality pact with Adolf Hitler.

events.description: World War II: The Battle of Rabaul commences Japan's invasion of Australia's Territory of New Guinea.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: The Battle of Rabaul commences Japan's invasion of Australia's Territory of New Guinea.

events.description: World War II: Troops of the British Eighth Army capture Tripoli in Libya from the German–Italian Panzer Army.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: Troops of the British Eighth Army capture Tripoli in Libya from the German–Italian Panzer Army.

events.description: World War II: German admiral Karl Dönitz launches Operation Hannibal.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: German admiral Karl Dönitz launches Operation Hannibal.

events.description: The Knesset resolves that Jerusalem is the capital of Israel.
events.html: • 1950 – The Knesset resolves that Jerusalem is the capital of Israel.

events.description: American inventor Walter Frederick Morrison sells the rights to his flying disc to the Wham-O toy company, which later renames it the "Frisbee".
events.html: • 1957 – American inventor Walter Frederick Morrison sells the rights to his flying disc to the Wham-O toy company, which later renames it the "Frisbee".

events.description: After a general uprising and rioting in the streets, President Marcos Pérez Jiménez leaves Venezuela.
events.html: • 1958 – After a general uprising and rioting in the streets, President Marcos Pérez Jiménez leaves Venezuela.

events.description: The bathyscaphe USS Trieste breaks a depth record by descending to 10,911 metres (35,797 ft) in the Pacific Ocean.
events.html: • 1960 – The bathyscaphe USS Trieste breaks a depth record by descending to 10,911 metres (35,797 ft) in the Pacific Ocean.

events.description: The Guinea-Bissau War of Independence officially begins when PAIGC guerrilla fighters attack the Portuguese Army stationed in Tite.
events.html: • 1963 – The Guinea-Bissau War of Independence officially begins when PAIGC guerrilla fighters attack the Portuguese Army stationed in Tite.[15]

events.description: The 24th Amendment to the United States Constitution, prohibiting the use of poll taxes in national elections, is ratified.
events.html: • 1964 – The 24th Amendment to the United States Constitution, prohibiting the use of poll taxes in national elections, is ratified.

entities.name: Twenty-fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution

events.description: Diplomatic relations between the Soviet Union and Ivory Coast are established.
events.html: • 1967 – Diplomatic relations between the Soviet Union and Ivory Coast are established.

events.description: Milton Keynes (England) is founded as a new town by Order in Council, with a planning brief to become a city of 250,000 people. Its initial designated area enclosed three existing towns and twenty-one villages. The area to be developed was largely farmland, with evidence of continuous settlement dating back to the Bronze Age.
events.html: • 1967 – Milton Keynes (England) is founded as a new town by Order in Council, with a planning brief to become a city of 250,000 people. Its initial designated area enclosed three existing towns and twenty-one villages. The area to be developed was largely farmland, with evidence of continuous settlement dating back to the Bronze Age.

entities.name: New towns in the United Kingdom

events.description: USS Pueblo (AGER-2) is attacked and seized by the Korean People's Navy.
events.html: • 1968 – USS Pueblo (AGER-2) is attacked and seized by the Korean People's Navy.

events.description: World Airways Flight 30 overshoots the runway at Logan International Airport in Boston, Massachusetts, and crashes into Boston Harbor. Two people are missing and presumed dead.
events.html: • 1982 – World Airways Flight 30 overshoots the runway at Logan International Airport in Boston, Massachusetts, and crashes into Boston Harbor. Two people are missing and presumed dead.[16]

events.description: The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame inducts its first members: Little Richard, Chuck Berry, James Brown, Ray Charles, Sam Cooke, Fats Domino, The Everly Brothers, Buddy Holly, Jerry Lee Lewis and Elvis Presley.
events.html: • 1986 – The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame inducts its first members: Little Richard, Chuck Berry, James Brown, Ray Charles, Sam Cooke, Fats Domino, The Everly Brothers, Buddy Holly, Jerry Lee Lewis and Elvis Presley.

entities.name: Rock and Roll Hall of Fame

events.description: Mohammed Said Hersi Morgan sends a "letter of death" to Somali President Siad Barre, proposing the genocide of the Isaaq people.
events.html: • 1987 – Mohammed Said Hersi Morgan sends a "letter of death" to Somali President Siad Barre, proposing the genocide of the Isaaq people.[17]

events.description: Madeleine Albright becomes the first woman to serve as United States Secretary of State.
events.html: • 1997 – Madeleine Albright becomes the first woman to serve as United States Secretary of State.

events.description: Netscape announces Mozilla, with the intention to release Communicator code as open source.
events.html: • 1998 – Netscape announces Mozilla, with the intention to release Communicator code as open source.

events.description: Five people attempt to set themselves on fire in Beijing's Tiananmen Square, an act that many people later claim is staged by the Chinese Communist Party to frame Falun Gong and thus escalate their persecution.
events.html: • 2001 – Five people attempt to set themselves on fire in Beijing's Tiananmen Square, an act that many people later claim is staged by the Chinese Communist Party to frame Falun Gong and thus escalate their persecution.

events.description: U.S. journalist Daniel Pearl is kidnapped in Karachi, Pakistan and subsequently murdered.
events.html: • 2002 – U.S. journalist Daniel Pearl is kidnapped in Karachi, Pakistan and subsequently murdered.

events.description: A very weak signal from Pioneer 10 is detected for the last time, but no usable data can be extracted.
events.html: • 2003 – A very weak signal from Pioneer 10 is detected for the last time, but no usable data can be extracted.

events.description: A 7.9 Mw  earthquake occurs in the Gulf of Alaska. It is tied as the sixth-largest earthquake ever recorded in the United States, but there are no reports of significant damage or fatalities.
events.html: • 2018 – A 7.9 Mw  earthquake occurs in the Gulf of Alaska. It is tied as the sixth-largest earthquake ever recorded in the United States, but there are no reports of significant damage or fatalities.

entities.name: List of earthquakes in the United States

events.description: A double car bombing in Benghazi, Libya, kills at least 33 people and wounds "dozens" of others. The victims include both military personnel and civilians, according to local officials.
events.html: • 2018 – A double car bombing in Benghazi, Libya, kills at least 33 people and wounds "dozens" of others. The victims include both military personnel and civilians, according to local officials.[18]

events.description: The China–United States trade war begins when President Donald Trump places tariffs on Chinese solar panels and washing machines.
events.html: • 2018 – The China–United States trade war begins when President Donald Trump places tariffs on Chinese solar panels and washing machines.[19]

events.description: Mutinying Burkinabè soldiers led by Paul-Henri Sandaogo Damiba depose and detain President Roch Marc Christian Kaboré amid widespread anti-government protests.
events.html: • 2022 – Mutinying Burkinabè soldiers led by Paul-Henri Sandaogo Damiba depose and detain President Roch Marc Christian Kaboré amid widespread anti-government protests.[20]

events.description: Northwestern Air Flight 738 crashes after takeoff from Fort Smith Airport, killing six people.
events.html: • 2024 – Northwestern Air Flight 738 crashes after takeoff from Fort Smith Airport, killing six people.[21]
